<paragraph blockId="7.[146,771,1459,1922]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis box="[146,496,1459,1479]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Variation and Differential Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The variation in appearance is striking (
<figureCitation box="[251,312,1489,1509]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[146,173,1819,1836]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,149,1778]" captionTargetId="figure-3@4.[146,1441,147,1783]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2. Examples of variants of male specimens of Vanewrightia kiesela sp. nov., collected at pyrrolizidine alkaloid baits during the day in Panguana/Peru (PH), showing the surprisingly large range of variation within a single population, sorted according to the amount of yellow on the upperside wings; left upperside, right underside. Details on specimen codes inTable 2. Scale bar = 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5384254" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5384254/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[360,372,1489,1509]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[146,173,897,914]" captionTargetBox="[148,768,149,858]" captionTargetId="figure-213@5.[146,770,147,862]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 3. Extreme variants of Vanewrightia kiesela sp. nov., arrows pointing to shared diagnostic characters; see text;left upperside,right underside.Details on specimen codes inTable 2. Scale bar = 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5384256" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5384256/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">3</figureCitation>
); whether or not we have seen all variants remains unknown―we assume that further variants are to be found. This makes a description as well as determination fraught with uncertainty and currently does not permit to give a robust differential diagnosis of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boppré &amp; Grados &amp; Laguerre &amp; Monzón" authorityYear="2020" box="[268,358,1606,1626]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Vanewrightia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kiesela">
<emphasis box="[268,358,1606,1626]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">V. kiesela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The existence of further specimens/species belonging to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boppré &amp; Grados &amp; Laguerre &amp; Monzón" authorityYear="2020" box="[268,391,1635,1655]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Vanewrightia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[268,391,1635,1655]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Vanewrightia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see below) increases the problem which is reviewed in Discussion.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[146,771,1459,1922]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Three kinds of variants, each variable, can be recognized: 1) forewings black, basally with some yellow in addition to yellow band, hindwings with some yellow or white within black margin, 2) forewings black with yellow band, hindwings with some yellow or white within black margin, 3) forewings black with yellow band, hindwings entirely black. A fourth kind (forewings with ± yellow in addition to yellow band, hindwings black) might be expected but has not been found. See Discussion for a parallel in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C.Felder &amp; R.Felder" authorityYear="1865" box="[491,625,1902,1922]" class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Chamaelimnas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[491,625,1902,1922]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Chamaelimnas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
butterflies.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[818,1442,1460,1539]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis box="[818,1040,1460,1480]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Similar-Looking Species.</emphasis>
Not only closely related (see below) but also several 
<emphasis box="[885,908,1491,1509]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">un</emphasis>
related moth and butterfly taxa, which resemble morphs of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boppré &amp; Grados &amp; Laguerre &amp; Monzón" authorityYear="2020" box="[818,902,1519,1539]" class="Insecta" family="Erebidae" genus="Vanewrightia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="kiesela">
<emphasis box="[818,902,1519,1539]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">V. kiesela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to a more or less high degree are considered in Discussion.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[818,1442,1588,1670]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis box="[818,894,1588,1608]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Biology.</emphasis>
Largely unknown. Males are diurnal and attracted to sources of pyrrolizidine alkaloids (= PA-pharmacophagous) but not or only very rarely to artificial light.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[818,1442,1719,1771]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis box="[818,939,1719,1739]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[944,1001,1720,1739]" name="Peru" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">PERU</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[1010,1095,1720,1739]" country="Peru" name="Huanuco" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Huanuco</collectingRegion>
and other regions, most likely also in other Latin American countries (see below).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[818,1442,1818,1926]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis box="[818,923,1818,1838]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Etymology.</emphasis>
The new species is dedicated to Anita Kiesel who assisted in a more than commendable way in MB’s laboratory for over 30 yr; the extra miles she went were always greatly appreciated and her work is acknowledged with cordial thanks.
</paragraph>
